<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[163,692,1366,1741]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
DEFINITION: The most recent common ancestor of 
<taxonomicName box="[283,404,1396,1419]" class="Reptilia" family="Iguanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Iguanidae</taxonomicName>
*, 
<taxonomicName box="[432,555,1396,1419]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Agamidae</taxonomicName>
* and 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Frost and Etheridge" authorityYear="1989" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Chamaeleonidae</taxonomicName>
, and all of its descendants (Estes et al., 1988).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[163,692,1366,1741]" lastBlockId="10.[739,1267,1276,1387]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
REMARKS: The monophyly of the Iguania is well supported by a number of character states (Estes et al., 1988). The Iguania include extant familial groups such as the 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Iguanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Iguanidae</taxonomicName>
*, 
<taxonomicName box="[286,412,1601,1624]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Agamidae</taxonomicName>
*, and the 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Frost and Etheridge" authorityYear="1989" class="Reptilia" family="Chamaeleonidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Chamaeleonidae</taxonomicName>
, and fossil groups such as the 
<taxonomicName authority="Gilmore, 1943" authorityName="Gilmore" authorityYear="1943" class="Reptilia" family="Arretosauridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Arretosauridae Gilmore, 1943</taxonomicName>
. The monophyly of the 
<taxonomicName box="[213,331,1689,1712]" class="Reptilia" family="Iguanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Iguanidae</taxonomicName>
* and the 
<taxonomicName box="[465,588,1689,1712]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Agamidae</taxonomicName>
* is still questionable (Frost and Etheridge, 1989), but there is evidence to support the splitting of the Iguania into two major subgroups: the nonacrodontan iguanians and the acrodontans (Macey et al., 1997).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
